	   <tr><td colspan=2>Kelethin at last!&nbsp;&nbsp;The plodding caravan finally ground its way around the last turning in the rutted road and that fairest of Elven Treehomes, Kelethin, could be seen high up in the trees.  We pulled up to the spot the Traders Guild representative had assigned to our caravan and we hurriedly set up the camp Kiunun'Or would use to trade out of while at Kelethin.<br><br>When we had finished, I went to the High Elf to collect my wages for the last six weeks.  Instead, he laughed and said &quot;Be off, boy.  You're no fit guard.  I have brought you to Kelethin.  Fed you for six weeks.  And now you expect me to pay you for it?  Go on, and try not to fall out of one of your precious trees.&quot;  With that he turned his back and walked away.<br><br>I stood there for several moments, shocked.  High Elves are known for their superior, high handed demeanor toward other races, even to us Woodland Elves, their closest cousins, but to actually be blatantly cheated by one.  I could hardly believe it.  He had fed me?  That was a laugh.  One taste of the camp food and I had decided to stick with what Kel had packed for me and what I could hunt and forage for on my own.  Even after sharing what I had with the other passengers I ate far better than the drivers and other guards.<br><br>The thrill of actually being in Kelethin would not let me dwell on it though.  I was in Kelethin now and would not miss the company of that High Elf and his sullen caravan so I turned and trotted down the path that led to one of the ingenious lifts that carried elves and goods between the city in the tress and the forest floor.<br><br>It has been many years since I was last in Kelethin; and even then I was not on my own.  As I mounted the ramp and stepped onto the waiting platform, I turned and considered the lever that activated the magic of the platform.  The last time I was here, I could not even reach the lever.  Father had held me up so I could place my hand on it.  Now I gathered my resolve, reached out, and confidently toggled the lever.  <br><br>In moments the platform had risen up into the treetops and come to rest at a loading platform.  I hurried off the platform as there was a crowd rushing to board the platform for the return trip to the forest floor.  The platform guard gave me directions to the Songweaver's Stump.  Fortunately it was just two platforms over so I didn't get lost in the confusing tangle of Kelethin's ramps, bridges, and multi-tiered platforms.<br><br>I stood for a while outside the doors of the Songweaver's Stump then took a deep breath, opened the door and entered the guild hall.  I asked for Sylia Windlehands and was directed toward an elf seated at the back of the hall.  She was leaning back in her chair, softly strumming a heavily decorated mandolin.  On the desk was a huge pile of papers that looked in danger of falling over sitting in a basket  labeled &quot;IN&quot; and two or three papers laying in the bottom of a matching basket labeled &quot;OUT&quot;.<br><br>She smiled as she saw me eye the leaning tower of papers on her desk and brought her tune to an end as she allowed her chair to come to rest on all four legs again.  &quot;Hello, I'm Sylia.  What can I do for such a handsome young Elf today?&quot; she said brightly, pointedly ignoring the impending paper avalanche.  &quot;My name is Talavir, son of Tyrion Watchwood and Sansa Evensong, and I wish to become a Bard and member of this Guild&quot;, I replied in a rush.   I pulled the scroll Aeolien had given me out of my tunic and handed it to her across the desk.  She considered the seal a moment before breaking it and reading what Aeolien had written.  Whatever it was, it must have been good because she stood and came around the desk to embrace me and said &quot;Well, of course, Talavir, welcome.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Here at Songweaver's, training is free but students are expected to provide their own instruments and any study materials such as song books, parchment, quills, and such.  Most of this can be purchased at special student pricing from the guild merchants out in the main hall.  How are you fixed for money?  Do you have a place to stay?&quot;<br><br>I felt my ears grow red as I admitted I had neither money nor a place to stay.  &quot;I thought I might camp in the forest until I could find work and…&quot;  <br><br>&quot;Oh, no, we can't have that&quot;, she interrupted.  &quot;In the first place, the forest around Kelethin is not as safe as it once was and it is not necessary in any case.  We have a small dormitory facility here for just these situations.  You are welcome to find a bunk and stay there for as long as you wish.  As for money, there is plenty of work available in Kelethin so you should have no problem finding something that will leave enough time for your studies here.  Why don't you go get settled in and let me know when you're ready to begin your training?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Thank you, thank you very much&quot;, I stammered.  After Kiunun'Or's treatment, the generosity of this Bard who had known me for only the few moments we had been talking was overwhelming.  &quot;Er, I wonder if I might ask one more favor?  Could you tell me the way to the hall of Faydark's Champions?&quot;<br><br>She nodded.  &quot;Yes, of course.  You would wish to look in on the Rangers, wouldn't you?  Take the bridge to your left as you leave here and then take another left up the ramp.  The Ranger Hall will be on the far side of the platform.  Oh, you'll also want to stop in at the bank and establish an account.  You can get to the bank by crossing straight across the platform rather than turning left to go to the Champions.&quot;<br><br>I thanked her again and headed toward the dormitory to see about a bed for the night and to stow my few things.  Sylia took one page off the &quot;IN&quot; stack wrote something on it and transferred it to the &quot;OUT&quot; basket before picking up her mandolin, leaning back in her chair, and resuming her tune with a smile.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Talavir<br>Elven Bard of the 4th Stanza</td></tr>
