	   <tr><td colspan=2>Aeolien roused Galen and I long before dawn.&nbsp;&nbsp;We wolfed down the bowl of hot porridge and cup of tea Kel handed us in the kitchen, grabbed lanterns, and raced out to the stables to harness the teams to the wagons.  The famous mists of Faydark lay curled deep and thick around the inn, reducing the lanterns to mere glowing globes as shouting men moved back and forth through it.  The wagon master and the drivers knew their business and the wagons of the small caravan were soon lined up and ready to resume the journey.<br><br>I had to hurry and stow the sack containing my few possessions aboard one of the wagons because Kel kept packing more and more food into it.  She already had so many sandwiches, travel biscuits, muffins, cookies, jerked beef and venison, fruit, vegetables from the garden, and I don't know what all else packed in there that I could hardly lift it into the wagon as it was.  All of this seemed to strike the wagon drivers and caravan guards as rather amusing.<br><br>After one last embrace, Kel shooed the girls back into the kitchen to begin the usual morning routine of the inn, leaving just me, Aeolien, and Galen standing together awkwardly in the quiet stillness of the dawn as we waited for the High Elf to appear.  I had thought that Galen might be upset by my departure but, if anything, he was more excited about it than I was.  He already had me returning at the head of my own army wearing a crown and carrying a magical sword and I hadn't even stepped off the porch yet.<br><br>At last Kiunun'Or came out of the inn, walked quickly to his horse, mounted, and with no more than a glance at the wagon master, turned and rode off into the thinning mist.  A growl from the wagon master got the wagons moving to follow the High Elf.  I shook hands with Aeolien and Galen one last time and hurried off to take my place in the wagon train.<br><br>Aeolien had arranged that I would be able to work off the fee for travelling within the protection of the caravan as far a Kelethin and have a little money in my pocket when I got there.  Officially, I was hired on as a caravan guard but in reality, my duties were those of a gopher.  &quot;Hey, boy, go fer firewood.&quot;  &quot;Boy, go fer water.&quot;  I didn't really mind all that much.  I wasn't a trained warrior or guard after all and the work was pretty much the same as I would have been doing back at the inn anyway.  I just wished they wouldn't take such obvious pleasure in ordering me about while they sat around, drank, and gambled.<br><br>It didn't take long to realize that Kiunun'Or ran a very different caravan from what I remembered of our troupe's caravan.   For one thing, the paths we took through the forest seemed chosen to avoid settlements rather than to seek them out.  For another, the guards only maintained a guard when we neared a village or crossed a path where one might expect to meet fellow travelers.  And yet when we passed through some of the darker regions of Faydark were a raid by bandits or Orcs was a real possibility I often patrolled alone while the guards got drunk in their tents.  When I suggested that perhaps mounting a larger guard might be a good idea to one of the drivers, he nodded to where the silhouette of the High Elf could be seen projected on the wall of his tent and muttered &quot;That one has no reason to fear attack.&quot;<br><br>The majority of the people in the caravan seemed to be directly employed by the High Elf himself.  There were only three other people who, like myself, were travelling with the caravan for safety.  They didn't seem to want to talk though.  Even my offer to share my food with them did little to encourage them; and the camp food was simply awful.  They had a bit of a haunted look about them, especially the girl who had dark circles under her sunken eyes and tended to stare blankly at nothing most of the time.  One day as we drew near Kelethin, I awoke to discover that they were gone.  A driver told me that they had reached the end of their journey and had left us.  Even though their company hadn't been much, I found I missed it and would be glad once we reached Kelethin.  <br><br>&nbsp;<br>Talavir<br>Elven Bard of the 4th Stanza</td></tr>
