	   <tr><td colspan=2>It was late morning, long after the usual crew of locals had broken their fast with Kel's hearty country fare of fresh bread with honey, steak, ham, eggs, biscuits and gravy and only a late-rising guest was still eating in the inn's common room when Rallos, Aeolien's large black dog began barking loudly out in the front yard.&nbsp;&nbsp;Rallos had more than a little wolf in him and was a good, smart watchdog so when he started such a racket we came quickly to investigate. <br><br>At the edge of the village and heading toward the inn was a small traders caravan lead by a stranger, a High Elf. Of course, where else would he be heading?  It wasn't so much that Aeolien's inn was in the center of the village but that it was the center of the village.  Everything took place there and the appearance of a caravan meant the arrival of news of the world beyond the village and the potential for profit and to obtain needed goods not generally available within the village itself.  By the time the caravan reached the inn, just about everyone in the village was already there.<br><br>As the trader drew near, Rallos put up such a violent display of barking and growling that Aeolien had Galen and I wrestle him around behind the inn and shut him in a storage shed while he greeted the trader.  Rallos stood with his legs set apart and braced with his chest out and every bit of fur on his neck and back standing right on end barking and growling fiercely.  He finally quieted down once we got him in the shed and the trader was out of sight, but he still stood stiffly on alert softly growling. Galen was as puzzled as I, we had never seen Rallos behave like that toward anyone much less an elf.  Although High Elves seldom passed through our little village, it wasn't as if he hadn't seen strangers at the inn before.  We put that mystery out of mind, however, and hurried in the back door of the inn to hear what news the trader had to tell.<br><br>Most of it was what must be the standard talk of traders in small out-of-the-way villages everywhere, the weather, past, present, and future, the price of corn or wheat or whatever was raised locally, stories of surpluses and shortages, far away wars and Orc raids, and on and on.  But then he mentioned something that snapped my head up with attention, his destination.  He and his caravan were travelling to Kelethin!<br><br>Aeolien noticed my sudden sharp attention and smiled somewhat sadly at me.  When I returned to the common room after finishing my afternoon chores he called me over.  &quot;Tal&quot;, he said, &quot;I've always suspected that one day you would leave us.  You're about the fidgetiest Woodland Elf I've ever met. There is no doubt you have the soul of a Bard.  Probably just like your parents did I imagine.  May they rest in Tunare's blessed embrace.  You're of that age now and, if you wish to, Kiunun'Or has agreed to see you through to Kelethin and let you work off your caravan fee on the way.&quot;<br><br>I could hardly believe my ears and my good fortune! And then, suddenly I felt my face redden and I had to turn away.  I was suddenly ashamed of being so eager to leave Aeolien and the home he had kindly opened to me when I had no other.  Tears stung my eyes as I realized how ungrateful I was acting and how much it would hurt Aeolien and Galen to see me go.  How would they run inn?  How could I even think of abandoning them and leaving them shorthanded? Aeolien was old when the Rangers brought me here, he needed me and the others.<br><br>He placed his arm on my shoulders and gently turned me back to face him.  &quot;Here, now, let's have none of that. Do you think so little of me to think that I would try to keep you here in this sleepy little village when I can see every fiber of your being longs to discover what's around the next turning of the road and the turning after that?  My own family was dead and buried many long years before the Rangers brought you to me.  Having you here to watch grow up into a fine young elf has given me more pleasure and pride than I thought I would ever see once I had lost my own sons.&quot;<br><br>&quot;My only regret is that this is the best that I can give you for your journey.&quot;  He reached down beside him and brought out a small bundle of new travelling clothes on which he had embroidered the Great Tree of the Woodland Elves.  On the tunic he had also embroidered a forest scene but if you looked at it just right you could see my father, mother, and little sister smiling, standing in the Mother's embrace and enveloped in Her warm glow.  <br><br>I had to wipe my eyes on my sleeve in order to see what he else he had placed on the table before me.  When I looked up, it was a scabbard with a sword!  &quot;I know we had to sell your father's fine sword a long time ago which I regret terribly and this one is certainly no match for it, but it is well made and cared for.&quot;  I pulled the short sword from the scabbard and the freshly honed and oiled blade gleamed in the afternoon sunlight.  Both sword and scabbard were well used, but Aeolien was right, they were well made, and if they were somewhat worn, they were also well cared for.  I sheathed the sword and Aeolien handed me two parchment scrolls that bore seals I had never seen before.  One looked quite old.  &quot;When you get to Kelethin, take this one to Sylia Windlehands at the Songweaver's Stump if she is still in charge of training there.  The other one take to the Champions of Faydark.  They will introduce you.  Now, go and tell Galen and pack up your things. Kiunun'Or means to have his business here complete by this evening and to press on at first light tomorrow.&quot;<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Talavir<br>Elven Bard of the 4th Stanza</td></tr>
