	   <tr><td colspan=2>March 23, 3213<br><br>I rose before dawn, slipped silently down from my upper bunk, and crossed to the small window at the other end of the room.&nbsp;&nbsp;I stared out moodily at the gray of the false dawn listening to the songs of the awakening birds and to the soft snores of Galen, my best friend and the person with whom I had shared these quarters in the attic of Aeolien's inn since the Rangers had brought me and what remained of our travelling troupe of minstrels and performers here after our caravan had been attacked and destroyed by Orcs.  <br><br>Galen is a half-elven boy several years younger than myself but already taller than me.  I could easily stand upright in our room even with the sharply slanted ceiling formed by the angled roof  of the inn.  Galen, however, was always knocking his head into a rafter or beam.  Being somewhat afraid of heights and of adding yet another bruise to his forehead, he preferred the lower bunk.  I, in the top bunk, could pretend I was sleeping on one of the high platforms of an elven treetop home.  Well, if I closed my eyes and ignored the rafters only inches from my nose anyway.<br><br>Galen and I were more or less apprenticed to Aeolien and worked about the inn doing whatever chores needed doing such as chopping firewood, carrying water from the stream that bubbled and splashed near  the inn, and caring for the inn's animals and livestock as well as the horses, mules, and other beasts guests at the inn might wish to have stabled during their stay.  Three young girls also worked at the inn primarily in the kitchen or as maids keeping the inn's rooms clean and comfortable.  Their room and the narrow hallway and stair took up the remaining three quarters of the attic. The two women who worked serving food and drink in the common room on the first floor slept elsewhere, sometimes in a guest's room on the second floor, sometimes in Aeolien's, sometimes in their own room they shared with the cook on the third floor.<br><br>I don't know exactly what I'd expected today when I awoke, but I thought I would feel… different somehow.  You see, today I was no longer an elfling.  I was an Elf.  Okay, a young elf, but an elf nonetheless, old enough now to choose my own way in the world. Unfortunately, today looked suspiciously similar to yesterday and pretty much every other day I'd known at the inn over the past few years.  I opened the window just as the sun flared above the horizon and the large rooster that reigned supreme over the courtyard below officially announced the beginning of a new day.<br><br>As I turned from the window Galen hit me in the face with his pillow touching off a furious but brief  pillow fight that ended when my pillow burst, covering Galen with feathers and down.  He emerged from the cloud with feathers in his hair, sticking out his ears and nose, and sneezing furiously as he tried to laugh and spit feathers out of his mouth at the same time.  We both collapsed on the floor laughing as the feathers drifted slowly down in the cold morning air, covering everything in the room.  We had just about recovered when Cylvia, still in her pajamas, poked her head through the door raising a new blizzard of feathers.  Galen and I looked at each other covered in feathers and burst out laughing anew.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sun Jan  6 22:27:10 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Talavir<br>Elven Bard of the 4th Stanza</td></tr>
