<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100858114890352></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100858114890352><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=128792&mid=100858114890352>The past as prolog</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=128792&mid=100858114890352#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=128792><span id= >Talavir</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Dec 17th 4:25 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am called Talavir. By the grace of the Mother, I am a wandering minstrel of the Woodland Elves of Faydark and this is my story. Unfortunately it is all too common a tale known to too many of this current, troubled Age.<br><br>I was born into a family of traveling troubadours. I tend to favor my mother with her brown hair and green eyes, though everyone who knew my father has always said they could see the elf in the elfling.&nbsp;&nbsp;We weren't wealthy, far from it, but we had more than some.  We owned the caravan wagon in which we lived as we toured the length and breadth of Faydark and the team that pulled it. Through the efforts of the troupe and Tunare's bounty of the Faydark Forest, we lacked for nothing.<br> <br>Father had been a soldier of no little renown in the Border Guards and his Sword Dance was always a popular part of our show. He didn't talk about his time with the Border Guards much but if you could catch him practicing the Dance when he thought was alone and unobserved it was something to see.  A certain intensity and seriousness would light up in his eyes and it was obvious he was no longer seeing the peaceful meadow and the empty practice yard but some other scene entirely. Then his sword would become nothing but a blur.  Every movement was graceful and economical and although the Dance maintained all the beauty it had when he performed for the public, it took on a grim lethality during those sessions that showed the master swordsman beneath the performer. With the sun glinting off his red-gold hair, the intensity of his flashing brown eyes, and the silver and gold blur of his blade, Death never looked so terribly beautiful.<br><br>Mother had a voice that could bring joy to the saddest breast or wring tears from the coldest, meanest heart. She also was an excellent archer and, more often than not to Father's feigned disgust, was the one actually responsible for the meat on our table. Woe be to any beast that caught the attention of those sharp green eyes while she had a bow or sling close to hand.<br><br>The druids had just confirmed that Mother was carrying my sister-to-be and we were returning to the safer confines of Greater Faydark around Kelethin when our caravan was attacked by a large raiding party of Orcs as we crossed through a clearing. The caravan guards and troupe members fought through the Orcs to reach the safety of the trees and the women and children were sent clambering into the treetops for safety. I think Father actually threw me most of the way up into the great tree before turning to do battle with the Orcs.  Mother sent me up into the cover of the canopy while she took a firing position and began loosing a flurry of deadly accurate shafts from her bow into the Orcs below.<br><br>From the safety of the treetop I watched Father Dance as I'd never seen him Dance before.  No Orc lived within reach of his blade.  Perched on a branch below, Mother was loosing shafts as quickly as she could draw her bow.  Even so, our little caravan was not equipped to fend off a raid of this size and the battle was turning against us.  Mother had just dropped some kind of Orc chieftain by burying a shaft into his left eye with such force that the arrow pierced the back of his helmet and protruded a good two or three inches out the back of his head when an Orc shaft took her in the throat. On bad nights I can still see the bright spray of blood, hear that sickening, wet gurgle that would have been her scream, and see her tumble off her perch into the raging battle below.<br><br>We were saved by the sudden appearance of a company of Rangers. You know Rangers, one second you're walking all alone through the forest and the next moment there is squad of Rangers at either elbow walking in step with you. Then before you can say anything, you're all alone again as if they had never existed.<br><br>This company was some of the largest Rangers I'd ever seen, being entirely made up of humans and half-elves. I'd seen humans before, but always as villagers or farmers or tradesmen and thought them kind of noisy and clumsy.  But the woodlore and fighting skills of these large Rangers were the equal of most Elven Rangers. If it weren't for the style of their fighting and their reliance on at least one human tongue when speaking together, I would have sworn they had Elven training.<br><br>They turned the tide of the battle and drove off the Orcs but our little caravan had taken a heavy blow.  Many were dead or dying or grievously wounded. Our wagon was burned along with most of what we had and the team was killed.  Father survived the battle with relatively minor wounds, but died within the week as several of the wounds festered and nothing could be done with them. The Rangers thought that perhaps several of the Orcs' weapons might have been poisoned. That was probably true, but after the loss of Mother I suspect Father lacked the will or desire to continue anyway and longed to join her in the Mother's embrace.<br><br>As the last remaining member of my family, the Rangers helped me perform the death rites for Mother and Father and the others who had fallen. They escorted those of us remaining to a nearby settlement, made sure we would be cared for, and then vanished into the forest. Being without family and with the troupe broken up, I was taken in as a kind of apprentice by old Aeolien, an innkeeper in the settlement. And there I stayed and worked until I came of age and decided to take formal training to become a Bard and study at the Songweaver's Stump in Kelethin.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Mon Dec 17 22:22:55 2001</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Talavir<br>Elven Bard of the 4th Stanza</td></tr>
